flowRoot.flowPara: > Open hardware encompasses the design of all kinds of objects. From electronic hardware with plans for a computer or a connected device to everyday goods: furniture, clothing, means of transport, etc.
> In principle, the documentation must be readable and understandable by a large audience and the components must be as accessible as possible so that these objects can be reproduced.
> Open hardware favours the repairability of objects. The production of components no longer depends on a single company; others can develop the know-how to reproduce them.
A material object whose blueprint can be freely used, modified and shared, enabling a whole range of open and decentralised collaborative practices.
By default, copyright gives exclusive use of a creation to its author, limiting its use and modification by third parties. This is known as copyright.
Copyleft is a legal strategy that uses copyright, through open licences such as creative commons, to allow others to use and modify a creation. It is a "reversal" of copyright.

3D printers can be used to reproduce certain types of object whose plans are made freely available. Prusa is a brand of 3D printer that has the particularity of having all its codes in open source as well as its hardware components in open hardware. The printer can then reproduce the printer, at least all the non-metallic parts, making certain repairs easier.
From these resources, derivative printers are invented by makers or organisations with specific needs.

The Mobility Factory [La fabrique Des Mobilités] was initiated in 2015 in France by ADEME (Environment and Energy Management Agency). This factory seeks to rethink mobility from the perspective of the commons. Among their activities, they are setting up an "Open Source Vehicle Community" focusing on intermediate vehicles, between the bicycle and the car. This commons-based factory model is spreading to other fields, with the Educational Commons Factory, the Geocommons Factory, the Health Factory, etc.

flowRoot.flowPara: A standard is a set of shared norms to simplify compatibility and communication between elements, rules to be followed when creating a solution so that it can interact with an ecosystem. Standards can be found everywhere: for hardware, software, data, etc. Standardisation encourages the development of other resources, without excluding a degree of customisation.
